Both critiques accepted — dropping BuildContext and BuildResult.

**New shape:**

```csharp
public interface IClass
{
    // existing surface...
    Task<Data> Build();  // optional default impl returns Data.Ok()
}
```

That's it. The action `@this` already carries its own args (source-generated properties) and reaches its Step (and through Step, the chain of sibling actions). Build() operates on `this`. No wrapper classes.

**Return convention via Data:**
- `Data.Ok("csv")` — success; Value carries the inferred terminal type name (or whatever build-time signal makes sense). The validator reads `Data.Value as string` and sets the terminal variable.set Type.
- `Data.Fail(error)` — Build() found a build-time error. Validator surfaces it; .pr emit fails.
- Build() that contributes nothing returns `Data.Ok()` (or just doesn't override — handlers without compile-time inference skip implementing it).

**Concrete per-action implementations get simpler:**

```csharp
// file.read
public Task<Data> Build()
    => Path.Value is string p && System.IO.Path.HasExtension(p)
        ? Task.FromResult(Data.Ok(MimeToType(System.IO.Path.GetExtension(p))))
        : Task.FromResult(Data.Ok());

// llm.query
public Task<Data> Build()
    => !string.IsNullOrEmpty(Schema.Value) ? Data.Ok("json")
     : !string.IsNullOrEmpty(Format.Value) ? Data.Ok(Format.Value)
     : Data.Ok();
```
